title: Training twice a day. via /r/Fitness
body:
I work right next to a gym and I’ve been thinking of going over during my lunch hour to do my main compound lifts when it’s quieter and then doing my accessory lifts after work.

Are there any negative aspects to training like this? Is it better to train in one session or does it not matter? I just want to save some more time.



Submitted November 13, 2018 at 02:10AM by -ce11ar-
via reddit https://ift.tt/2qIiPvp

summary: Feeling groggy after intense workouts via /r/Fitness
title: Feeling groggy after intense workouts via /r/Fitness
body:
I sleep about 8-10 hours per night, but recently I’ve been waking up lethargic and slow. It’s not until about 12 pm that I finally feel ‘awake’.

I train over 5x per week and definitely making gains.

I eat around 200g of protein a day and weigh 86kg at 182cm.

I’ve tried to cut carbs down from my diet.

Any ideas how to fix this?

Thanks in advance.



Submitted November 13, 2018 at 04:14AM by Avocado_Sex
via reddit https://ift.tt/2QFOmJO

title: Parents put nature in the shopping basket
body:

In a world of vast consumer choice, ambiguous product descriptions and self-appointed experts, parents face a minefield when picking out food, toys or other products for their children. A new qualitative study indicates that naturalness is the current benchmark for consumer choice among parents.

summary: Family, school support makes kids more likely to stand up to bullying
title: Family, school support makes kids more likely to stand up to bullying
body:
Family, school support makes kids more likely to stand up to bullying

A recent study finds young people with good family relationships are more likely to intervene when they witness bullying or other aggressive behavior at school — and to step in if they see victims planning to retaliate. The study found that kids who were already excluded, or discriminated against by peers or teachers, were less likely to stand up for victims of bullying.

summary: Cancer stem cells get energy from protein, and it's proving to be their Achilles' heel
title: Cancer stem cells get energy from protein, and it's proving to be their Achilles' heel
body:
Cancer stem cells get energy from protein, and it’s proving to be their Achilles’ heel

A new study shows that cancer stem cells switch from metabolizing sugar to metabolizing protein. Clinical trial based on this observation may revolutionize care for older adults with acute myeloid leukemia.

title: Don’t Settle for Living Half-Alive
body:
Don’t Settle for Living Half-Alive

“Who you are is what you settle for, you know?” ~Janis Joplin

I spent several years in a state of light depression without noticing.

Why was it only “light”? Because I was functional: I went to work every morning, I managed to feed myself (mostly with convenience food, but still). My house was reasonably livable, though far from sparkling clean. And I wasn’t particularly sad, nor was I ever even…

summary:
I can't even begin to tell you how many times in my, now over 20 year, fitness career I've heard this. 🙄
▪
It takes about 3500...
caption:
I can’t even begin to tell you how many times in my, now over 20 year, fitness career I’ve heard this. 🙄
▪
It takes about 3500 excess calories to gain 1 pound of fat…👉 and that’s not going to happen over night.
▪
There are so many factors that go into apparently quick weight gain and women, I’m sorry to tell you but you have the most problems with this. 😖
▪
This is why it’s important to focus on other things than weight alone. Energy levels, how your clothes are fitting or even do the “pinch test.”
▪
👌 Pinch several areas on your body you’d like to go down…you’ll know whether you’re pinching less or more.
▪
✔ So don’t focus so much on the scale and don’t be too upset if you’re up a pound or two…even several…over a day - it’s most likely just water and food.
▪
Your friend,
Advomatt
▪
▪
